I chose Homework 3 because it helped me connect heat transfer analysis to systems I already find interesting. I enjoyed fluid mechanics last year, and turbines appear in many engineering systems. Working through the turbine blade problem showed how conduction, convection, and contact resistance work together in one model. Comparing the blade with and without the thermal barrier coating made the temperature changes across each layer clear. The ceramic coating adds resistance to heat flow and keeps the superalloy blade below its allowable temperature. This showed how heat transfer equations guide real turbine design.
<br>
This assignment also felt important because mechanical engineering includes systems such as HVAC, where heat transfer control matters. Before this course, I mostly understood how these systems operate at a basic level. This homework helped me understand the heat transfer mechanisms behind that operation. It gave me a deeper view of how engineers manage temperature through material selection and layered structures. This type of analysis appears in many mechanical systems, so learning how to model heat flow through components will be useful in future engineering work.
